SUMMARY:CCD Seminar Series with Professor Khuhly Robin
DESCRIPTION:Professor Robin brings this deep expertise in colonial govern
 ance and indigenous political structures to bear on a topic of direct rel
 evance to students of constitutional law and legal history. His talk\, "C
 olonial State\, Traditional Elites and Political Dualism in Mizoram\," ex
 amines how colonial authority and hereditary chieftainship functioned as 
 a negotiated\, interdependent system of governance and how its eventual u
 nraveling shaped the constitutional arrangements under the Sixth Schedule
  and the political trajectory of the region through 1966.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Professor Robin brings this deep expert
 ise in colonial governance and indigenous political structures to bear on
  a topic of direct relevance to students of constitutional law and legal 
 history. His talk\, "Colonial State\, Traditional Elites and Political Du
 alism in Mizoram\," examines how colonial authority and hereditary chieft
 ainship functioned as a negotiated\, interdependent system of governance 
 and how its eventual unraveling shaped the constitutional arrangements un
 der the Sixth Schedule and the political trajectory of the region through
  1966.&#160\;</p>
