  at University of Chicago.Â 
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;Title: Societal impact and the ivory tower: an generat
 ive AI perspective  &#160\;Abstract: It is undeniable that computing rese
 arch has the power to rapidly reshape the world we live in\, and AI is li
 terally proving this point in real time. But even as we push to improve t
 hese models and architectures\, we are seeing today how economic motives 
 are shaping messaging and perception around AI's limitations and harms\, 
 posing ethical questions most of us are ill-equipped to answer. In this t
 alk\, I argue that we CS researchers must be more accountable for not jus
 t our research results\, but how they are deployed in applications. Recog
 nizing such impacts is arguably a very challenging task itself. Using my 
 own experience in recent AI security projects\, I describe the duality of
  AI's impact today\, both in real harms it has produced via misuse\, and 
 in protective benefits it can provide. I share some of the ethical questi
 ons we faced when considering the design and deployment of our tools Glaz
 e and Nightshade\, and our experiences through this process. Finally\, I 
 suggest some takeaways\, including possible perspectives on evaluating ne
 w research directions through an ethical downstream lens\, as well as som
 e concrete research questions that offer potential for positive technical
  and societal impact.  &#160\;  Ben Zhao is Neubauer Professor of Compute
 r Science at University of Chicago. He completed his Ph.D. at U.C. Berkel
 ey (2004)\, and B.S. from Yale (1997). He is a Fellow of the ACM\, TED/AI
  speaker\, and a recipient of the NSF CAREER award\, MIT Technology Revie
 w's TR-35 Award (Young Innovators Under 35)\, TIME100/AI (100 Influential
  people in AI)\, USENIX Internet Defense Prize\, Concept Art Association'
 s Community Impact Award\, ComputerWorld Magazine's Top 40 Technology Inn
 ovators award\, IEEE ITC Early Career Award\, and Faculty awards from Goo
 gle\, Amazon\, and Facebook. His work has been covered by many media outl
 ets including New York Times\, CNN\, NBC\, ABC\, BBC\, MIT Tech Review\, 
 Wall Street Journal\, Forbes\, and New Scientist. His current research fo
 cuses on mitigating the harms of misused AI. He has published over 190 ar
 ticles in areas of security and privacy\, machine learning\, networking\,
  and HCI. He served as TPC (co-)chair for the World Wide Web conference (
 WWW 2016) and ACM Internet Measurement Conference (IMC 2018)\, and on the
  Steering Committee of IEEE Conference on Secure and Trustworthy Machine 
 Learning (SaTML).
