  and the ivory tower: an generative AI perspective</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>
 <strong>Abstract:</strong> It is undeniable that computing research has t
 he power to rapidly reshape the world we live in\, and AI is literally pr
 oving this point in real time. But even as we push to improve these model
 s and architectures\, we are seeing today how economic motives are shapin
 g messaging and perception around AI's limitations and harms\, posing eth
 ical questions most of us are ill-equipped to answer. In this talk\, I ar
 gue that we CS researchers must be more accountable for not just our rese
 arch results\, but how they are deployed in applications. Recognizing suc
 h impacts is arguably a very challenging task itself. Using my own experi
 ence in recent AI security projects\, I describe the duality of AI's impa
 ct today\, both in real harms it has produced via misuse\, and in protect
 ive benefits it can provide. I share some of the ethical questions we fac
 ed when considering the design and deployment of our tools Glaze and Nigh
 tshade\, and our experiences through this process. Finally\, I suggest so
 me takeaways\, including possible perspectives on evaluating new research
  directions through an ethical downstream lens\, as well as some concrete
  research questions that offer potential for positive technical and socie
 tal impact.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>  Ben Zhao is Neubauer Professor of Com
 puter Science at University of Chicago. He completed his Ph.D. at U.C. Be
 rkeley (2004)\, and B.S. from Yale (1997). He is a Fellow of the ACM\, TE
 D/AI speaker\, and a recipient of the NSF CAREER award\, MIT Technology R
 eview's TR-35 Award (Young Innovators Under 35)\, TIME100/AI (100 Influen
 tial people in AI)\, USENIX Internet Defense Prize\, Concept Art Associat
 ion's Community Impact Award\, ComputerWorld Magazine's Top 40 Technology
  Innovators award\, IEEE ITC Early Career Award\, and Faculty awards from
  Google\, Amazon\, and Facebook. His work has been covered by many media 
 outlets including New York Times\, CNN\, NBC\, ABC\, BBC\, MIT Tech Revie
 w\, Wall Street Journal\, Forbes\, and New Scientist. His current researc
 h focuses on mitigating the harms of misused AI. He has published over 19
 0 articles in areas of security and privacy\, machine learning\, networki
 ng\, and HCI. He served as TPC (co-)chair for the World Wide Web conferen
 ce (WWW 2016) and ACM Internet Measurement Conference (IMC 2018)\, and on
  the Steering Committee of IEEE Conference on Secure and Trustworthy Mach
 ine Learning (SaTML).</p>
