SUMMARY:The influence of the American model on French constitutional cult
 ure
DESCRIPTION:The presentation specifically aims to measure the influence o
 f the American model on French political literature in the 19th century\,
  continuing into the present day. From the French Revolution of 1789 onwa
 rds\, American institutions are primarily linked to the virtue of probity
 . American democracy is thought to be predisposed to combat any form of c
 orruption and to exercise reasonable freedom\, tempered by moral determin
 ations and political institutions preventing any concentration of power. 
 In this framework\, the reality of the American Constitution is not fully
  grasped. The foundational works of Tocqueville and Ă‰douard de Laboulaye
 \, while addressing certain principles of the American political system\,
  tend to entrench these distorting beliefs. Essentially\, the overwhelmin
 g dominance of the English monarchical model leads most authors to carica
 ture American political institutions. The English monarchy would frame de
 mocracy due to its customary nature and the existence of a parliamentary 
 aristocracy that sociologically and legally links the executive power to 
 the legislative power. Indeed\, certain institutional projects and a bias
 ed reading of the Constitution of the French Second Republic (1848) may h
 ave foreshadowed an internalization of the American model. However\, this
  model was rarely used\, as it was only partially understood. It was only
  under the Fifth Republic\, particularly in the 1970s\, that the politica
 l and institutional model made a resurgence. American power became associ
 ated with the personal embodiment of executive power\, which sparked a fa
 scination with presidentialism in France. By the late 2000s\, a second ph
 ase was reached with the establishment of constitutional justice modeled 
 on judicial review\, as well as the unsuccessful strengthening of the leg
 islative chambers' control powers. The conference hopes to spark interest
  in the circulation of ideas and representations generated by the constru
 ction of constitutional models.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The presentation specifically aims to m
 easure the influence of the American model on French political literature
  in the 19th century\, continuing into the present day. From the French R
 evolution of 1789 onwards\, American institutions are primarily linked to
  the virtue of probity. American democracy is thought to be predisposed t
 o combat any form of corruption and to exercise reasonable freedom\, temp
 ered by moral determinations and political institutions preventing any co
 ncentration of power. In this framework\, the reality of the American Con
 stitution is not fully grasped. The foundational works of Tocqueville and
  Ă‰douard de Laboulaye\, while addressing certain principles of the Ameri
 can political system\, tend to entrench these distorting beliefs. Essenti
 ally\, the overwhelming dominance of the English monarchical model leads 
 most authors to caricature American political institutions. The English m
 onarchy would frame democracy due to its customary nature and the existen
 ce of a parliamentary aristocracy that sociologically and legally links t
 he executive power to the legislative power. Indeed\, certain institution
 al projects and a biased reading of the Constitution of the French Second
  Republic (1848) may have foreshadowed an internalization of the American
  model. However\, this model was rarely used\, as it was only partially u
 nderstood. It was only under the Fifth Republic\, particularly in the 197
 0s\, that the political and institutional model made a resurgence. Americ
 an power became associated with the personal embodiment of executive powe
 r\, which sparked a fascination with presidentialism in France. By the la
 te 2000s\, a second phase was reached with the establishment of constitut
 ional justice modeled on judicial review\, as well as the unsuccessful st
 rengthening of the legislative chambers' control powers. The conference h
 opes to spark interest in the circulation of ideas and representations ge
 nerated by the construction of constitutional models.&#160\;</p>
